Analyze Deleted Files with Sleuth Kit/Autopsy
Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Install and configure Sleuth Kit and Autopsy on Linux
Create forensic disk images for analysis
Use Sleuth Kit command-line tools to locate and recover deleted files
Analyze deleted files using Autopsy's graphical interface
Cross-reference findings between both tools
Document forensic evidence of deleted file recovery
Prerequisites
Basic Linux command-line knowledge
Understanding of file systems (ext4, NTFS)
Familiarity with forensic investigation concepts
Root/sudo access on the Linux machine
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated Linux environment. The provided machine is bare metal with no pre-installed forensic tools, so you will install all required software during the lab.

Task 1: Environment Setup and Tool Installation
Subtask 1.1: Update System and Install Dependencies
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y
sudo apt install -y build-essential git wget curl unzip default-jdk
Subtask 1.2: Install Sleuth Kit
sudo apt install -y sleuthkit
tsk_version
Subtask 1.3: Install Autopsy
wget https://github.com/sleuthkit/autopsy/releases/download/autopsy-4.20.0/autopsy-4.20.0.zip
unzip autopsy-4.20.0.zip
cd autopsy-4.20.0
sudo ./unix_setup.sh
Subtask 1.4: Create Test Environment
# Create a test disk image with files to delete
dd if=/dev/zero of=test_disk.img bs=1M count=100
mkfs.ext4 test_disk.img

# Mount the image
sudo mkdir /mnt/test_disk
sudo mount -o loop test_disk.img /mnt/test_disk

# Create test files
sudo mkdir /mnt/test_disk/documents
sudo echo "This is a confidential document" > /tmp/secret.txt
sudo echo "Financial records for 2024" > /tmp/finance.txt
sudo echo "Employee database backup" > /tmp/employees.txt
sudo cp /tmp/*.txt /mnt/test_disk/documents/

# Create additional files in root
sudo echo "System configuration backup" > /mnt/test_disk/config.bak
sudo echo "Important project notes" > /mnt/test_disk/notes.txt

# Unmount to simulate real scenario
sudo umount /mnt/test_disk
Task 2: Use Sleuth Kit to Locate and Analyze Deleted Files
Subtask 2.1: Mount and Delete Files
# Remount the disk
sudo mount -o loop test_disk.img /mnt/test_disk

# Delete some files
sudo rm /mnt/test_disk/documents/secret.txt
sudo rm /mnt/test_disk/config.bak
sudo rm /mnt/test_disk/notes.txt

# Empty trash and sync
sudo sync
sudo umount /mnt/test_disk
Subtask 2.2: Analyze File System Structure
# Display file system information
fsstat test_disk.img

# List all inodes (including deleted)
ils test_disk.img

# Show detailed inode information
istat test_disk.img 12
Subtask 2.3: Recover Deleted Files with Sleuth Kit
# Create recovery directory
mkdir recovered_files

# List deleted files
fls -d test_disk.img

# Recover deleted files by inode
icat test_disk.img 12 > recovered_files/recovered_secret.txt
icat test_disk.img 13 > recovered_files/recovered_config.bak

# Verify recovered content
cat recovered_files/recovered_secret.txt
cat recovered_files/recovered_config.bak
Subtask 2.4: Search for File Signatures
# Search for specific file patterns
sigfind -t fat test_disk.img
blkls test_disk.img | strings | grep -i "confidential"
Task 3: Cross-reference Results with Autopsy
Subtask 3.1: Start Autopsy Server
cd autopsy-4.20.0
sudo ./bin/autopsy &
Open web browser and navigate to: http://localhost:9999/autopsy

Subtask 3.2: Create New Case in Autopsy
Click New Case
Enter case details:
Case Name: Deleted_Files_Analysis
Description: Lab 4 - Deleted File Recovery
Investigator: Student
Click New Case
Subtask 3.3: Add Evidence Source
Click Add Host
Host Name: test_system
Click Add Host
Click Add Image
Location: Browse to your test_disk.img file
Type: Disk
Import Method: Copy
Click Next and Add
Subtask 3.4: Analyze Deleted Files in Autopsy
Navigate to File Analysis → File Activity Time Lines
Click Generate
Review the timeline for deleted file activities
Navigate to Keyword Search
Search for: confidential
Review results and compare with Sleuth Kit findings
Subtask 3.5: Extract Deleted Files via Autopsy
Go to File Analysis → File Search
Check Show only deleted files
Click Search
Right-click on deleted files
Select Extract File(s)
Save to autopsy_recovered/ directory
Task 4: Compare and Document Results
Subtask 4.1: Compare Recovery Results
# Compare files recovered by both tools
ls -la recovered_files/
ls -la autopsy_recovered/

# Compare file contents
diff recovered_files/recovered_secret.txt autopsy_recovered/secret.txt
Subtask 4.2: Generate Analysis Report
# Create comprehensive report
cat > analysis_report.txt << EOF
DELETED FILE ANALYSIS REPORT
============================

Case: Lab 4 - Deleted File Recovery
Date: $(date)
Analyst: Student

SLEUTH KIT FINDINGS:
- Total deleted inodes found: $(ils test_disk.img | wc -l)
- Successfully recovered files: $(ls recovered_files/ | wc -l)
- File signatures detected: $(sigfind -t fat test_disk.img | wc -l)

AUTOPSY FINDINGS:
- Deleted files identified: $(ls autopsy_recovered/ | wc -l)
- Timeline entries: Generated successfully
- Keyword matches: Found in deleted content

CROSS-REFERENCE RESULTS:
- Both tools successfully identified deleted files
- Content integrity verified through diff comparison
- Autopsy provided enhanced visualization and reporting

CONCLUSION:
Both Sleuth Kit and Autopsy effectively recovered deleted files.
Sleuth Kit offers precise command-line control while Autopsy
provides comprehensive GUI-based analysis and reporting.
EOF

cat analysis_report.txt
Verification and Testing
Verify Tool Installation
# Confirm Sleuth Kit installation
which fls && which icat && which ils

# Test Autopsy accessibility
curl -s http://localhost:9999/autopsy | grep -i autopsy
Validate Recovery Success
# Confirm file recovery
file recovered_files/*
wc -l recovered_files/*

# Verify content integrity
grep -i "confidential" recovered_files/recovered_secret.txt
Troubleshooting
Issue: Autopsy web interface not accessible Solution:

sudo netstat -tlnp | grep 9999
sudo ufw allow 9999
Issue: Permission denied during file recovery Solution:

sudo chown $USER:$USER recovered_files/
chmod 755 recovered_files/
Issue: Disk image mounting fails Solution:

sudo losetup -d /dev/loop0
sudo umount /mnt/test_disk 2>/dev/null
Cleanup
# Stop Autopsy
sudo pkill -f autopsy

# Clean up files
sudo umount /mnt/test_disk 2>/dev/null
rm -rf test_disk.img recovered_files/ autopsy_recovered/
rm -rf autopsy-4.20.0/ autopsy-4.20.0.zip
Conclusion
You have successfully completed deleted file analysis using both Sleuth Kit and Autopsy. This lab demonstrated how command-line forensic tools like Sleuth Kit provide precise control over file recovery operations, while GUI-based tools like Autopsy offer comprehensive analysis workflows and enhanced visualization capabilities.

Key accomplishments include:

Installing and configuring professional forensic tools
Creating realistic test scenarios with deleted files
Recovering deleted files using multiple methodologies
Cross-referencing results between different forensic platforms
Documenting findings in a professional forensic report
These skills are essential for digital forensics investigations, incident response, and data recovery operations in cybersecurity environments.
